What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 171305 entries and 8 columns in the dataset, Explainig the duration minutes, start/end time and start/end station names.There are other categoral variables such as the user type and gender.

What are the main features of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm more interested in figuring out These questions

Questions

  • which gender has the most trips?

  • Which user type has the most trips?

  • Is it bike share for all trip?

  • What are the most popular/used start or end stations?

  • How long does the average trip take?

  • When are most trips taken in terms of time of day or day of the week?

  • How long does the average trip take if a user is a subscriber or customer?

  • Who is more consumption of daily trips?Customers or subscripers?

  • Do customers take longer bike trips than subscribers?

  • Do customers take longer bike trips on average than subscribers throughout the day?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your features of interest?¶

Trip duration, start/end station name, start/end time, gender and user type.

In [14]:
#plot the count of trips for each gender

gender=df.member_gender.value_counts()
n_gender=gender.sum()
gender_order=gender.index
base_color=sb.color_palette()[0]
plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 12.0

sb.countplot(data=df, x='member_gender',order=gender_order,color=base_color)

plt.xlabel('Gender')
plt.title('Count of trips by gender')
    #print the proportion text on the bars of each gender
for i in range (gender.shape[0]):
    # Remember, gender contains the frequency of unique values in the `member_gender` column in decreasing order.
    count = gender[i]
    # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
    precentage_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_gender)
    # Print the string value on the bar. 
    plt.text(i, count+1000, precentage_string, ha='center')
    
# we can remove the top and right axis using rcParams:
#plt.rcParams["axes.spines.right"] = False
#plt.rcParams["axes.spines.top"] = False;

Discuss the distributions of your variables of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Based on the distributions the percentage of male members were more than females. And most of trip users were subscribers rather than customers. when analyzing the days of week, there were more trips on weekdays than weekends, with Tuesdays having the highest frequency of bike rides than any other day. And most of the trips were on peack hours 8a.m and 17p.m . finally, The majority of members did not use bike sharing for all of their trips.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There is some problem to this Ford GoBike data, such as:

  • Quality issues for many columns, such as the dtype is not suitable with it's data.
  • We have to add some column(hour, day) from start time column for analysis.
  • The trip duration were in secounds and i converted them to minutes to be easier to understand.
  • When plotting out the trip duration, it was messy so i used xlim() to zoom in to closer range where most trip durations fell. Then i droped the rows which had duration minutes greater than the limited range.

Conclusions¶

The following are the main findings from the above exploratory analysis using univariate, bivariate, and multivariate visualization for the Ford Gobike dataset.

  • There are more male members in Ford GoBike than females. almost 76.2% of the users are male, and 23.8% are females.

  • The majority of members who participate in the Ford GoBike trips were subscribers not customers.

  • Most of GoBikes users did't use bike share for all of their trips.

  • When analyzing the day of weeks, bike trip patterns were different on weekdays than on weekends. There is higher frequency of bike trips on weekdays than on weekends, and most of the trips started on Tuesday and Thursday.

  • When analyzing the time of bike trips, GoBike users are most frequent during the peak hours.

  • Customers took longer time to complete the trip than subscribers.

  • Regardless of the user type, male members appear to complete the trip faster than females.
